#  Good to have multiple gitignore files 
#   - web/.gitignore was auto-generated by Vite's scaffolding — it knows what Vite/Node projects
#    produce (node_modules, dist, *.local, etc.)
#   - The root .gitignore handles Python/backend concerns (.venv, __pycache__, .env)
#   - If you merge them into one, you lose the clean separation and future web/ tooling won't
#   know where to put its gitignore entries

#  How gitignore works with multiple files?
#  Git applies gitignore rules from all .gitignore files in the repo, but each file's rules
#  only apply to files at or below that file's directory. Rules are evaluated in order of
#  specificity — the deepest .gitignore wins for files in its subtree:
#  1. Global gitignore (~/.gitignore_global or core.excludesFile)
#  2. Root .gitignore
#  3. web/.gitignore (for anything inside web/)

#  What about conflicts?
#  There are no real "conflicts" — deeper rules win. If root .gitignore says ignore *.log and
#  web/.gitignore says !*.log, then *.log files inside web/ are un-ignored. Files outside web/
#  still follow the root rule.

# Logs
logs
*.log
npm-debug.log*
yarn-debug.log*
yarn-error.log*
pnpm-debug.log*
lerna-debug.log*

node_modules
dist
dist-ssr
*.local

# Editor directories and files
.vscode/*
!.vscode/extensions.json
.idea
.DS_Store
*.suo
*.ntvs*
*.njsproj
*.sln
*.sw?

# Frontend
!.env # We want to commit the .env file in the frontend
!.env.production # Production API URL — safe to commit (public value)